\pard\plain \sl240\slmult0\widctlpar \f4\fs20 {\cs16\super #} HIDM_EDITFILE}}{\b\f2 Edit Cards command (File menu)}{\f2 
\par }\pard \sl240\slmult0\widctlpar {\f2 
\par Use this command to edit existing Flash study cards or add new ones.
\par 
\par }\pard \sl240\slmult0\widctlpar {\f2 A question is entered (or edited) in the upper box labeled Question, and the answer that matches that question is put in the second box labeled Answer. 
This Question and the Answer make up the two sides of a Flash study card which (if saved) will be added to the current Flash study file.
\par }\pard \sl240\slmult0\widctlpar {\f2 \{bml EditCard.bmp\}
\par 
\par The Edit Cards dialog box offers the following options :
\par }\pard \sb60\sl240\slmult0\widctlpar {\b\f2 New
\par }\pard \li360\sl240\slmult0\widctlpar {\f2 Save the current study card, then create a new blank card ready for the next entry.
\par }\pard \sb60\sl240\slmult0\widctlpar {\b\f2 Delete
\par }\pard \li360\sl240\slmult0\widctlpar {\f2 Delete the current study card, then display the next card in the study file.
\par }\pard \sb60\sl240\slmult0\widctlpar {\b\f2 Prior
\par }\pard \li360\sl240\slmult0\widctlpar {\f2 Display the card preceding the current card in the study file.
\par }\pard \sb60\sl240\slmult0\widctlpar {\b\f2 Next
\par }\pard \li360\sl240\slmult0\widctlpar {\f2 Display the next card in the study file.
\par }\pard \sb60\sl240\slmult0\widctlpar {\b\f2 Apply
\par }\pard \li360\sl240\slmult0\widctlpar {\f2 Save the current study card but do not create a new one or quit the edit dialog.
\par }\pard \sb60\sl240\slmult0\widctlpar {\b\f2 Ok
\par }\pard \li360\sl240\slmult0\widctlpar {\f2 Save the current study card and quit the edit dialog.
\par }\pard \sb60\sl240\slmult0\widctlpar {\b\f2 Cancel
\par }\pard \li360\sl240\slmult0\widctlpar {\f2 Quit the edit dialog but do not save the current card.
\par }\pard \sl240\slmult0\widctlpar {\f2 \page }{\cs16\super #{\footnote \pard\plain \sl240\slmult0\widctlpar \f4\fs20 {\cs16\super #} HIDM_CLEARSTATS}}{\b\f2 Clear Statistics command (File menu)}{\f2 
\par }\pard \sl240\slmult0\widctlpar {\f2 
\par Use this command to clear all of the statistics kept by Flash.
\par }\pard \widctlpar {\f2 \page }{\cs16\super #{\footnote \pard\plain \sl240\slmult0\widctlpar \f4\fs20 {\cs16\super #} HIDM_MULTIPLECHOICE}}{\b\f2 Multiple Choice command (Test menu)}{\f2 
\par }\pard \sl240\slmult0\widctlpar {\f2 
\par Use this command to test using Multiple Choice mode.
\par 
\par }\pard \sl240\slmult0\widctlpar {\f2 A question is displayed in the top box labeled Question and various possible answers are displayed in the middle box. At 
least one of the answers matches the question displayed. Your task is to choose which answer is correct by double clicking on it with the left mouse button (you can also select among the possible answers using the arrow keys to scroll up or down and then 
pressing Enter when the selection you choose is highlighted). Only the first line of each possible answer is displayed in the selection box, however the full text of each answer is displayed in the lower box as it is highlighted.
\par }\pard \sl240\slmult0\widctlpar {\f2 
\par }\pard \widctlpar {\f2 If you select the correct 
answer then not much will appear to happen: the Flash Statistics dialog box will be updated and a new test question will be presented. However if you select an incorrect answer then another dialog box will pop up to inform you that the answer was wrong an
d will show you both the question and the correct answer. }
\par \pard \sl240\slmult0\widctlpar {\f2 
\par }\pard \sl240\slmult0\widctlpar {\f2 \{bml mchoice.bmp\}\page }{\cs16\super #{\footnote \pard\plain \sl240\slmult0\widctlpar \f4\fs20 {\cs16\super #} HIDM_SHOWANSWER}}{\b\f2 Honor System command (Test menu)}{\f2 
\par }\pard \sl240\slmult0\widctlpar {\f2 
\par Use this command to test using the Honor System.
\par 
\par }\pard \sl240\slmult0\widctlpar {\f2 A question is displayed in the Flash programs main window. Your task is to think of the correct answer, then press the \ldblquote Show Answer\rdblquote 
 button, then compare the answer given to that which you had in mind. You alone decide if the two match (that\rquote s why it\rquote s called the Honor System) and then press the \ldblquote Yes\rdblquote  or \ldblquote No\rdblquote 
 button in response to the question \ldblquote Did you get it right?\rdblquote .
\par }\pard \sl240\slmult0\widctlpar {\f2 
\par }\pard \sl240\slmult0\widctlpar {\f2 Here is an example which shows the Honor System dialog box after pressing the \ldblquote Show Answer\rdblquote  button:
\par }\pard \sl240\slmult0\widctlpar {\f2 
\par \{bml QandA.bmp\}
\par }\pard \sl240\slmult0\widctlpar {\f2 \page }{\cs16\super #{\footnote \pard\plain \sl240\slmult0\widctlpar \f4\fs20 {\cs16\super #} HIDM_TYPEINANSWER}}{\b\f2 Type In Answer command (Test menu)}{\f2 
\par }\pard \sl240\slmult0\widctlpar {\f2 
\par Use this command to test using the Type In method.
\par 
\par }\pard \sl240\slmult0\widctlpar {\f2 A question is displayed in the Flash programs main window. Your task is to type the correct answer into the Type In Answer dialog box, pressing Enter when done. 
\par }\pard \sl240\slmult0\widctlpar {\f2 
\par In this example the answer given was \ldblquote b\rdblquote .
\par 
\par \{bml TypeIn.bmp\}
\par 
\par }\pard \sl240\slmult0\widctlpar {\f2 
